{"author":{"id":"02ecfeec5e3d9ae3fcb4ee7636634148fee4f97bfc8cfa132041bf8882dd22ae"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1458734821,"nonce":"25ouQ1rnl1kj1Y1oYM/yRuEbNB4=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDIwMDMyMzQxOA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/693#issuecomment-200323418"},"message":"Hi Bjorn,\n\nThanks for initiating this idea.  I think it is an excellent idea and could complement the information shared during the Training Days.  The IUC is a principle component in the success of Galaxy, and I think that exposure like this benefits both the IUC and the Galaxy community.  A component of the IUC charter should be a constant effort to acquire additional good-standing members to help oversee the addition of new Galaxy utilities and maintenance of existing utilities.\n\nUnfortunately I won’t be attending the GCC again this year as my current organization does not support it.  Let me know if there is anything I can do to help though and I’ll try my best (my bandwidth is currently stretched thin).  ;)\n\nGreg Von Kuster\n\n\u003e On Mar 22, 2016, at 12:47 PM, Björn Grüning notifications@github.com wrote:\n\u003e \n\u003e Dear @galaxyproject/iuc https://github.com/orgs/galaxyproject/teams/iuc!\n\u003e \n\u003e GCC is coming and the talk deadline is this Friday. \n\u003e Do we want to present the IUC and recent tool development features at the GCC. I guess we have enough to present and give a round-up of the last years.\n\u003e \n\u003e members and especially new members\n\u003e statistics about the repo/work\n\u003e best practice guidelines\n\u003e community involvement (3 IUC codefests so far)\n\u003e driving new technologies (Tool syntax enhancements)\n\u003e macros\n\u003e macro-inheritence\n\u003e template-input\n\u003e sections\n\u003e tool profiles\n\u003e new test capabilities\n\u003e dependencies - IUC is providing a lot of tool_dependencies for the entire community\n\u003e conda dependency - TNG dependency management\n\u003e starforge/bioarchive/cargo-store/ ?\n\u003e automated testing of tools with github/planemo/travis\n\u003e we offer Galaxy Tool dev workshops like the one at GCC\n\u003e Is this interesting enough to apply for a talk and tell the community more about our work? Anyone wants to give this talk or/and help to work on it?\n\u003e \n\u003e —\n\u003e You are receiving this because you are on a team that was mentioned.\n\u003e Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/693","files":null}]}